{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.3 Basic & Advanced Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As the {\i QuestWorlds} engine is oriented towards rules-light play, we designate some mechanics as \u8220"Basic\u8221" and others as \u8220"Advanced.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Basic rules represent the minimum mechanical structure you need to play a game with the feel of {\i QuestWorlds}, while advanced rules add mechanical depth to areas of play which you might wish to emphasize, though possibly at a cost in speed of play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this document, we put advanced mechanics in their own section from the relevant basic mechanic section.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The advanced mechanics can be added to play individually; you do not have to bring them in together. In cases where an optional mechanic depends upon or interrelates with another optional mechanic, we note that in the text.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If this is your first time reading these rules, you may wish to skip over these sections. Return to them once you understand the basic mechanics. Similarly, if this is your first time playing these rules, you may wish to omit the advanced rules at first, getting a feel for the game in its simplest form, and then add them in as you want more depth. Your GM may even decide to employ certain advanced rules on a case by case basis, providing more detail or nuance to particularly interesting conflicts where beneficial, while otherwise taking a lighter approach.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 1.3.1 Who Is This Document For\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The primary audience for this document is game-designers who wish to utilize the {\i QuestWorlds} rules framework to implement their own game.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We also recognize that some people will use this document to learn about the {\i QuestWorlds} system before purchasing it, and some players in games were the GM has a rule book, may use this as a reference to help understand the rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For that latter reason, we address the rules here to a player.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, this remains a technical document with few examples, advice, or other non-rules text to help you play your game, as such are beyond the scope of this System Reference Document.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is expected that the designers of games you play based on these rules will include such guidance and context as is relevant to their game\u8217's particular genre or setting, presented in a format better suited for learning how to play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.4 Numbering\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sections within this document are numbered. This is for the benefit of game designers and reviewers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This does not imply that game designers need number the rules in their own games.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Numbering however makes it easy to refer to rules in this document when page numbers may vary by presentation format for the purposes of error trapping or tracking changes. If you need to give us feedback about this document, that will assist us.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.5 Participants\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 1.5.1 Players\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You and your fellow players each create a Player Character (PC) to be the \u8220"avatar\u8221" or \u8220"persona\u8221" whose role you will play in the game. The PCs pursue various goals in an imaginary world, using their {\b abilities}, motivations, connections, and more to solve problems and overcome {\b story obstacles} that stand in their way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When we say \u8216'you\u8217' in this document we may mean the player or their PC. Which should be clear from context, or explicitly noted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 1.5.2 Game Master\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your Game Master (GM) is the interface between your imagination and the game-world in which the PCs have their adventures; describing the people, places, creatures, objects, and events therein. Your GM also plays the role of any Non-Player Characters (NPCs) with whom your PC interacts in the course of your adventures.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We generally refer to the GM as \u8216'your GM\u8217' in this document\u8217's player-facing language. However, if you are the GM for a given game, this naturally refers to you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 2.0 Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a {\i QuestWorlds} game, stories develop dynamically as you and your GM work together to role-play the dramatic conflict between your group\u8217's PCs in pursuit of their goals and the challenges, or threats that your GM presents to stand in your way. Stories advance by two methods: conflict, where your PC is prevented from achieving their goals because there is something that must be overcome, a {\b story obstacle}, to gain a desired person, thing, or even status: the {\b prize}; or revelation, where something must be overcome, a {\b story obstacle}, to learn a secret, uncover the past, or reach understanding: the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Over the course of play, your GM will present various {\b story obstacles} as conflicts to the PCs, resulting in either {\b victory} or {\b defeat} for your character, which determines whether or not you gain the {\b prize} you sought. These conflicts can represent any sort of challenge you might face: fighting, a trial or debate, survival in a harsh environment, out-wooing rival suitors, and so on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rather than mechanically addressing the individual tasks that make up these conflicts, {\i QuestWorlds} usually assesses your overall {\b victory} or {\b defeat} in a single {\b contest} where you and your GM make an opposed roll pitting your characters {\b ability} vs the {\b resistance} the {\b story obstacle} presents to you achieving the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Whenever the GM presents a {\b story obstacle} for you to overcome, you should {\b frame the contest} by describing what you are trying to accomplish, the {\b prize}, and which of your {\b abilities} (see below) you want to use to achieve that {\b prize}, and how.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Based on that {\b framing} and other factors, your GM will assess what {\b resistance} the characters face.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You roll a twenty-sided die (D20) against your PC\u8217's {\b ability}, and your GM rolls a D20 against the {\b resistance}. Your GM will assess your overall {\b victory} or {\b defeat} in the contest based on the {\b success} or {\b failure} of both rolls, and narrates the results of your attempt to overcome the {\b story obstacle} and gain the {\b prize} accordingly. The direction of the story changes, in either a big or small way, depending on whether you gain the {\b prize} or not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We encourage your GM to work with your suggestions when narrating the {\b victory} or {\b defeat}, but the final decision rests with them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.1 Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters in {\i QuestWorlds} are defined by the {\b abilities} they use to face the challenges that arise in the course of their story. Rather than having a standard list of attributes, skills, powers, etc. for all characters, anything that you can apply to solve a problem or overcome a {\b story obstacle} could be one of your {\b abilities}. While your GM may provide some example {\b abilities} to choose from that connect your PC to a particular story or game world (whether created by your GM or by the designer of a particular game), you get to make up and describe most or all of your {\b abilities}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some {\b abilities} might be broad descriptions of your background or expertise, like \u8220"Dwarf of the Chalk Hills\u8221" or \u8220"Private Detective\u8221" - implying a variety of related capabilities. Others might represent specific capabilities or assets such as \u8220"Lore of the Ancients,\u8221" \u8220"Captain of the Fencing Team,\u8221" or \u8220"The Jade Eye Medallion.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ultimately, {\b abilities} are just names for the interesting things your character can do.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.1.1 Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character may have one or more {\b flaws}. A {\b flaw} is an {\b ability} that you do not use to accomplish something, but instead the GM uses to hinder you from accomplishing something, or invokes to force you to act a certain way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flaws} maybe psychological weaknesses such as \u8220"Alcoholic\u8221" or \u8220"Heroin Addict\u8221", or physical weaknesses such as \u8220"One-Eye,\u8221" \u8220"Wheelchair-Bound\u8221" or \u8220"Asthmatic.\u8221" A {\b flaw} might also be a moral philosophy such as \u8220"Code Against Killing,\u8221" \u8220"Pacifist,\u8221" or \u8220"Radical Candor\u8221" that limit your behavior in some way. A {\b flaw} also might be a relationship such as a \u8220"Frail Aunt,\u8221" \u8220"Single Dad,\u8221" or \u8220"Blackmailed\u8221".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many {\b flaws} describe attributes that can be viewed positively. By making it a {\b flaw} and not an {\b ability} you are inviting your GM to use it to make your life more difficult, not easier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You should not use your {\b flaw} to accomplish something; if you feel that is likely, make it an {\b ability} and flag to your GM that you want them to draw on it as a {\b flaw} at appropriate moments. In that case, record both an {\b ability} and a {\b flaw} with the same name.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ultimately, in {\i QuestWorlds} a {\b flaw} is simply something that you invite the GM to use to hinder or prevent your character doing something. In return for the GM exercising the {\b flaw} you gain {\b experience points} (see \u167?8.1).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.1.2 Scores, Ratings and Masteries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i QuestWorlds} {\b abilities} are {\b scored} on a {\b rating} of 1\u8211-20, representing the {\b target number (TN)} you need to roll or less to succeed on your roll during a {\b contest} (see \u167?2.3 for more details).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once your {\b ability} passes 20, you would always be able to roll under it on a D20. So to allow abilities to scale over 20 {\b scores} we use of tiers of capability we refer to as {\b Mastery}. To reflect abilities (or {\b resistance}s) higher than 20, either permanently through character advancement or a temporarily with {\b modifier} to a contest roll, note a {\b mastery} for every 20 points in the ability, and treat what remains as the {\b rating}. So, for an {\b ability} of 27, we note one {\b mastery} and a {\b rating} of seven written as \u8220"7M\u8221" and we write the {\b rating} of 21, as 1M.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The \u8220"M\u8221" after the {\b rating} signifies {\b mastery}. The number in front of the M is the {\b rating}, and represents the new {\b target number} you seek to roll or less. Whatever your roll, the mastery then {\b bumps} your {\b result}. You {\b bump} a {\b success} to a {\b critical}, and {\b bump} a {\b failure} to a {\b success}. If you roll a {\b critical} you can {\b bump} down your opponent. When both you and the resistance have {\b masteries} they cancel each other out.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Having a {\b mastery} means that you {\b succeed} most of the time and {\b critical} more often; you will only {\b fail} when you roll a {\b fumble}, and have a higher chance of a {\b critical} from rolling under the {\b TN}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, Trevor Okafor is trying to hover a helicopter over a ravine so that Bethany Ng can winch down to a stranded climber in high cross-winds. The GM calls for a roll. Trevor Okafor has 31 in Pilot, written as \u8220"11M\u8221". Trevor\u8217's player rolls against a {\b TN} of 11. They roll a 17 and fail, but Trevor\u8217's {\b mastery} means the actual {\b result} is {\b bumped} up to a {\b success} on a 17. This beats the GM\u8217's {\b success} on a 13. Later Bethany Ng is trying to stabilize the victim on the route back to hospital. Bethany has 27 in Medic, written as \u8220"7M\u8221". Bethany\u8217's player rolls against a TN of 7. They roll a 4 and succeed, but the {\b mastery} means that the actual {\b result} is bumped up to a {\b critical} on a 4, which beats the GM\u8217's {\b success} on a 14.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Specific {\i QuestWorlds} games or genre packs may use other symbols relevant to their setting or genre to denote {\b mastery} instead of M. If so, this should be clearly noted by their designers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a {\b score} climbs, you may even gain multiple {\b masteries} in it. {\b Mastery} tiers above one (representing an overall {\b score} or 41 or more) are marked with a number to the right of the M symbol. Each successive {\b score} increase over 20 becomes a new {\b mastery} tier. Thus, if you have 10M2, you have two {\b masteries} and a {\b rating} of 10, (representing a total {\b score} of 50). 10M3 means that you have three {\b masteries} and a {\b rating} of 10, and so on. Multiple {\b masteries} result in multiple {\b bumps} up, so with two {\b masteries} a critical {\b bumps} to a success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To simplify {\b bumping}, when both you and the resistance have {\b masteries} they cancel out.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See \u167?2.3.7 for more details on {\b bumps}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.1.2.1 No Relevant {\b ability}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may sometimes be faced with a {\b story obstacle} for which you have no relevant {\b ability} whatsoever. In such cases, you may still enter into conflict with the {\b story obstacle} using a minimum base {\b target number} of 6 for your {\b contest} roll. Like {\b scores}, it may also be subject to {\b modifiers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.1.2.2 Using Scores As thresholds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i QuestWorlds} treats {\b scores} as a measure of how effective you are at solving problems with the {\b ability}, and does not limit what you can do with that {\b ability}, provided your actions are credible in genre. Where an important part of the genre is that certain uses of the {\b ability} are only available when you pass a threshold of experience, often through overcoming story obstacles to improve the {\b ability} in game, you may chose to set threshold for those {\b abilities}. For example, a magic system might classify certain supernatural effects as Apprentice, Journeyman, or Master level, and require {\b ratings} of 15, 5M, or 1M2 (respectively) in a relevant {\b ability} to even attempt them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Such departures from abstraction should generally only be made where the increased complexity they bring leads to rewarding choices in a key area of interest to the setting or genre at hand. In most cases, you and your GM can simply follow the fiction surrounding your {\b ability} and its context within the setting for guidance as to what applications of the {\b ability} are credible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.2 Possessions and Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character will generally be considered to have whatever equipment is reasonably implied by your abilities. Having an \u8220"Athenian Hoplite\u8221" {\b ability} will mean that your character possesses bronze armor, a shield, a spear, and a short-sword; while a \u8220"Country Doctor\u8221" would be expected to have a well-stocked medical-bag and possibly a horse & buggy in the right setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, if you wish your character to possess something that is particularly special, interesting, or unusual, you may also enumerate it as a rated {\b ability} in its own right, just like any other {\b ability} your character might use to solve a problem.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In play, the degree to which you can overcome {\b story obstacles} with your possessions depends not on any qualities inherent to the objects themselves, but to the {\b score} of your relevant {\b ability}. However the significance of various sorts of gear lies in the types of actions you can credibly propose, and what their impact might reasonably be. An \u8220"Invisibility Cloak\u8221" {\b ability} implies very different fictional capabilities than \u8220"Souped-up Muscle Car\u8221" does.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conversely, if in the course of play you find your character in a situation without equipment essential to utilize an ability effectively, or where your character\u8217's gear is poorly suited to the task at hand, your GM may take into account in assessing credibility-based {\b modifiers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.2.1 Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In {\i QuestWorlds}, wealth is treated as just another way to overcome {\b story obstacles}. Many characters may not even have an explicit wealth {\b ability}, with their wealth or assets instead implied by {\b abilities} representing their background, profession, or status. Whether explicit or implied, the relevant {\b score} is not an objective measure of the size of your fortune, but instead indicates how well you solve problems with money and resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.3 Contest Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You choose an {\b ability} relevant to the conflict at hand, describe exactly what you are trying to accomplish, and how. Your GM may modify these suggested actions to better fit the fictional circumstances, and describe the actions of the NPCs or forces on the other side of the conflict.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.1 Resolution Methods\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The basic resolution methods are as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.1.1 Assured Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some {\b obstacles} don\u8217't require a roll to overcome. You\u8217'll just do it and keep going, much as you get dressed in the morning or drive your car to work. We call these kinds or contests {\b assured} contests because your {\b victory} is assured. Your GM may want to describe your {\b victory} as a sweat inducing challenge for you, even though there is no risk of {\b defeat}, to highlight the heroic struggle of your PC to beat the obstacle, nonetheless.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As your character advances, the challenges that qualify for assured contests will become more complex. If you face a driving challenge, the bar for assured will be much lower for a champion Formula 1 racer than a typical commuter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Assured contests} are the GM\u8217's primary tool to establish your character\u8217's competence. This makes them one of the most powerful and frequently used tools in a GM\u8217's tool chest. Remember, your GM doesn\u8217't have to, and usually shouldn\u8217't advise you you\u8217're involved in an {\b assured contest}, so it\u8217's best to treat all {\b contests} as if your skin is on the line.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may also use an {\b assured contest} when there is no interesting story branch from {\b defeat}. If failing to open the derelict spaceship\u8217's hatch means that the story of your exploration of the ancient space hulk would end abruptly, your GM may choose to make it an {\b assured contest}. {\b Assured contests} may be used to find clues when your GM is running a mystery and correct application of one of your {\b abilities} should reveal the information and allow the story to continue, over becoming mired due to a missed roll and missing clue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes your GM will decide potential complications could arise in overcoming an {\b story obstacle}. Or they may want to give you a {\b bonus} if you do particularly well. If so, they will call for you to make a die roll even though your {\b victory} is not in question. Your GM will use your die roll {\b result} to decide if any unforeseen {\b consequences} or {\b benefits} arose from your actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you roll a {\b failure}, you still beat the obstacle, but you also suffer an adverse {\b consequence} (see \u167?2.7). The nature of this adversity is up to the GM. It will probably be a {\b penalty} involving the same tactic you used in this one (because you exhausted yourself, sprained an ankle, embarrassed yourself in front of your peers, etc.) or to the value of one of your relationships.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you achieve a high {\b result}, you\u8217'll receive a {\b benefit} from your effort (see \u167?2.6). Again, this is up to the GM to define. It could be a {\b bonus} to the {\b tactic} used in the {\b contest}, or to of one of your relationships, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fumbles} and {\b criticals} always result in an unexpected difficulty or reward!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An {\b assured contest} can be summarized as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab You and your GM agree upon the terms of the {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab The GM may decide that you simply gain the {\b victory} and there are no {\b consequences} or {\b benefits} beyond that.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab If not the GM conducts a contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab You roll a D20 vs your relevant {\b ability}, while your GM rolls a D20 vs the {\b resistance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Your GM compares the {\b success} or {\b failure} of the two rolls, and assesses any {\b consequences} or {\b benefits}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Your GM then narrates how you obtained your {\b victory} and any {\b benefits} or {\b consequences} that arose.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.1.2 Simple Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b simple contest} is {\i QuestWorlds}\u8217' primary resolution mechanic for overcoming {\b story obstacles}, and is used the most often where the outcome is uncertain. It also provides the foundation for other types of uncertain {\b contest}, including several {\b long} ones. As such, it receives both an overview of key concepts here as well as a more detailed treatment in \u167?4.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b simple contest} can be summarized as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab You and your GM agree upon the terms of the {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab You roll a D20 vs your relevant {\b ability}, while your GM rolls a D20 vs the {\b resistance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Your GM compares the {\b success} or {\b failure} of the two rolls, and assesses your overall {\b victory} or {\b defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Your GM then narrates the {\b outcome} of the conflict as appropriate.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you enter into conflict with another player rather than a {\b story obstacle} presented by your GM, you both roll your relevant abilities for the {\b contest} instead of against a GM-set {\b resistance}, and your GM interprets the {\b results}, as described above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.2 Framing the Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.2.1 Contest Framing Overview\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a conflict arises during the game, you and your GM start by clearly agreeing on:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What goal you are trying to achieve. We call this the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What the {\b story obstacle} is you are trying to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What {\b tactic} you are using to and overcome it.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This process is called {\b framing the contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.2.2 Conflict: Goals vs Obstacles\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contests} in {\i QuestWorlds} don\u8217't simply tell you how well you performed at a particular task: they tell you whether or not you overcame a {\b story obstacle}, which moves the story in a new direction. Unlike some other roleplaying games, a {\b contest} in {\i QuestWorlds} does not resolve a task, it resolves the whole {\b story obstacle}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you need secret records which are stored in a vault within a government compound, your goal is to get the information - while the fact that it is secured against your access is a {\b story obstacle} you must overcome to attain that goal. Overcoming that {\b story obstacle} may involve many possible tasks, evading guards, lock-picking, forging credentials, etc. - but the {\b contest} doesn\u8217't address those individually. The {\b contest} is framed around the entire conflict against the {\b story obstacle} as a whole.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a fight, your {\b story obstacle} may be the opponents themselves, who you are fighting to capture or kill. Just as often you are seeking another goal and you might just as easily attain it by incapacitating or evading your foes. In this case, beating the enemy is a task, not the {\b story obstacle}. For example, if an {\b ally} has been accused of treason by the King, your goal could be to prove the {\b ally\u8217's} innocence. The power of the King threatening your {\b ally} is a {\b story obstacle} to be overcome, and a trial by combat could be a {\b contest} to resolve the conflict with an {\b ability} like \u8220"Knight Errant.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a court trial, your goal is likely a particular verdict, while the {\b story obstacle} might be the opposing lawyer, an unjust law, or even the justice system itself. In this case, jury selection, a closing argument, revelatory evidence, or legal procedural challenges are tasks, not the entire {\b story obstacle}. The overall conflict encompasses all those things.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A conflict to overcome a {\b story obstacle} moves the story forward when it is resolved. If it is merely a step toward resolving a {\b story obstacle} it is a task and not a conflict. While those component tasks may be interesting parts of narrating {\b tactics} and {\b results}, your GM should be sure to look for the {\b story obstacle} in conflict when framing a {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there is no {\b story obstacle} to your actions, your GM should not call for a {\b contest} but simply let you narrate what you do, provided that seems credible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, you are traveling from one star system to another. In the next star system you hope to confront the aged rebel who holds long-forgotten secrets that could bring freedom to the galaxy. Your GM feels there is no useful {\b story obstacle} for you to {\b contest} against, and so lets you describe heading down to the spaceport to secure a ship, meeting the captain and crew of your vessel, and traveling to the next world. Your GM encourages you to summarize what happens quickly so you can get to the meeting with the old rebel. Your GM knows that will be the real {\b story obstacle}, convincing the old rebel to part with their secrets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.2.3 Tactics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You either choose an {\b ability} that represents any \u8216'key moment\u8217' in overcoming that {\b story obstacle}, or a broad {\b ability} that lets you overcome the whole {\b story obstacle}. We call this choosing a {\b tactic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b rating} from your {\b ability score}, after adding any {\b augment} (see \u167?2.5) or {\b modifiers} (see \u167?2.4), relevant {\b consequences} or {\b benefits} (see \u167?2.6) is your {\b target number}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your {\b tactic} might describe your using an {\b ability} that helps you overcome a task within the {\b story obstacle}: sneaking past the guards, picking the locks, choosing the right jury or skewering your opponent with your foil. Or, your {\b tactics} might describe using a broad ability like \u8220"Ninja\u8221", \u8220"Lawyer\u8221", or \u8220"Fencer\u8221" to overcome all those challenges that might form part of the {\b story obstacle}. Either way, if you succeed at that roll, you overcome the whole {\b story obstacle}. Or by failing at that roll, you fail to overcome the {\b story obstacle}, not just fail at one task.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When deciding on your {\b tactic}, focus on how your unique abilities would help you overcome the {\b story obstacle}. This as the \u8220"key moment\u8221" where we focus on your PC. Use this moment to reveal your PC\u8217's strengths to the group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will determine if your {\b tactic} passes a {\b credibility test}. If you try to jump a 100 meters gap or run faster than a speeding car, your action is not credible and your GM will ask you to choose a different {\b tactic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Credibility depends on the genre, as what is not credible in a gritty police procedural might be in pulp where you might be able to leap from a bridge onto a speeding train. If in dispute, your GM should discuss with the group whether they consider your {\b tactic} credible for the genre.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extraordinary abilities} in some genres give you the capability to do the incredible. For example in a superhero genre you might fly or be invulnerable to bullets, in a fantasy genre hurl magical lightning bolts. A genre pack for the game should help define what incredible {\b tactics} are allowed for that game as part of an {\i Extraordinary Powers Framework}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GM can narrate the remaining tasks that make sense of the story depending on your {\b success} with that roll, or have them occur \u8216'off-stage\u8217' for speed. Think of the way TV or Cinema often cuts to the key moment of drama in a break-in, over showing us the whole heist from beginning to end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.2.4 No Repeat Attempts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b contest} represents all of your attempts to overcome a {\b story obstacle}. If you lose it means that no matter how many times you tried to solve the problem, you finally had to give up. You can try again only if you use a new {\b tactic} to overcome the {\b story obstacle}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.3 Rank\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM uses a {\b rank} when choosing to adjust a {\b target number}. That adjustment may come from an {\b augment} (see \u167?2.5), {\b modifier} (see \u167?2.4), {\b benefits} or {\b consequences} (see \u167?2.7). Your GM also uses the same {\b rank} when determining the {\b resistance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Bonuses to the dice roll use the scale of values: +3, +6. +9, +M, +M2 Penalties to the dice roll use the scale of values: -3, -6, -9, -M, -M2\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You should be able to memorize these values in play, and just go up or down the scale, instead of translating a {\b rank} to a value. For convenience the following table shows the scale of {\b ranks}.\par}
