{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 8.0 Experience\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During a session of play your character will have the chance to learn from experience or overcoming personal obstacles. When your character learns, they gain a {\b experience points}. {\b Experience points} can be used to improve your character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 8.1 Earning Experience Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You gain one {\b experience points} for any of the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When your {\b outcome} for a {\b contest} is a {\b defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your GM uses a {\b flaw} or other {\b ability} against you in a contest with you (see \u167?2.6). This happens either when the story forced you to confront a {\b flaw}, or the GM gave you a {\b hindrance} (see \u167?3.4), if the {\b hindrance} results in a {\b penalty}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You do not gain {\b experience points} if any of the following apply:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You only gain an {\b experience point} for each of your {\b abilities} or {\b flaws} once in a session of game play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You do not get {\b experience points} for an {\b augment}, {\b AP gifting} or {\b assist}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You do not gain an {\b experience point} from an {\b assured contest}, even if you roll to determine {\b benefits} or {\b consequences}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can gain a maximum of five {\b experience points} in any one session. Once you have earned five {\b experience points}, you cannot gain further {\b experience points} in that session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.1.1 Experience on Defeat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Awarding {\b experience points} on {\b defeat} is a self-correction mechanism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It slows your advance if your PC regularly outclass the {\b resistance}. This pushes your GM to introduce threats that {\b credibly} present a greater threat to your PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If you regularly buy off {\b defeat} with {\b story points} you will find it harder to advance. In {\i QuestWorlds} your GM should provide an entertaining story branch on defeat; you should not need to buy {\b defeat} off, unless it damages your character conception or is the climax.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the GM finds that the PCs are no longer regularly earning {\b experience points} they can consider using {\b resistance progression} (see \u167?2.8) to increase the {\b base resistance} so that more {\b contests} will feature a high enough resistance to earn {\b experience points}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 8.2 Improving Your Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you accumulate 10 {\b experience points}, you can buy an {\b advance}. An {\b advance} allows you to select two of the following. You cannot choose an element more than once.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab +9 to a standalone {\b ability} or breakout {\b ability}; or +6 to a {\b keyword}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab +6 to a standalone {\b ability} or breakout {\b ability}; or +3 to a {\b keyword}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a new standalone {\b ability} at 13; or a new breakout {\b ability} at + 1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a new standalone {\b ability} at 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Turn a stand-alone {\b ability} into a {\b keyword} by adding a new +1 breakout {\b ability} to it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Drop a {\b flaw}, or turn it into an {\b ability} if story appropriate and agreed with the GM.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition, if you have less than three {\b flaws}, you may add another, provided it fits the story, when you take an {\b advance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some genres you may wish to maintain a tally of the total {\b experience points} earned as a measure of your reputation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.2.1 Catch-Ups\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To encourage well-rounded characters, a package deal, called a {\b catch-up}, becomes available whenever you acquire via improvement a new {\b mastery} in one of your {\b abilities} ({\b keyword} or stand-alone). Any time one of your {\b scores} crosses a {\b mastery} threshold (i.e.\u160?20 -> 21, 40 -> 41, etc). you may also improve up to three {\b abilities} or {\b keywords} of your choice by three points each, as long as the chosen {\b abilities} are currently rated five or more points lower than your newly adjusted {\b scores} in the raised {\b ability} that triggered the {\b catch-up}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may not increase the bonus of {\b breakout abilities} under a {\b keyword} with a {\b catch-up}, nor does net effective value of a breakout {\b ability} crossing a {\b mastery} threshold trigger a {\b catch-up}. Only a {\b keyword}\u8217's base {\b scores} is considered in this context.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.2.2 Rate of Advancement\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We assume an average earning rate of two {\b experience points} per session. This would lead to you gaining an advance every five sessions. If your rate is lower than one {\b experience point} a session, your GM should choose one of these options:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Provide more credible threats\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use {\b resistance progression}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Reduce the cost of an {\b advance} to five {\b experience points}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.2.2 Directed Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On occasion your GM may increase one of your {\b abilities}, by +3, +6 or +9, or give you a new {\b ability}, usually rated at 13. These are called {\b directed improvements}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Directed improvements} are usually rewards for overcoming particularly important or dramatic {\b story obstacles}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will tend to use them to raise {\b abilities} that would otherwise fall behind, but should increase due to story logic, or introduce new {\b abilities} for the same reason.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM might give you a new {\b flaw} to represent a story outcome from a contest, that leads you with a hindrance to future action. If you have three or more {\b flaws} you can ask your GM to drop one in favor of the new {\b flaw}, if you it seems story appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.2.3 Timing of Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your improvements happen immediately, when you cross the threshold to buy an {\b advance}, or a GM awards you a {\b directed improvement}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 8.3 Milestone Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may decide that they do not want to track {\b experience points} earned during a game. In this case they may switch to {\b milestone improvement}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Under {\b milestone improvements} the GM simply declares that your PCs have reached a point in the story where we should see them improve their {\b abilities} and award you an {\b advance} (see \u167?8.2).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM should not use both {\b experience points} and {\b milestone improvements} but choose one. If in doubt, choose {\b experience points} as the default. {\b Milestone improvements} do not naturally balance against the {\b resistance} and the GM may need to use {\b resistance progression} to continue to up the threat level against your PCs (see \u167?2.8).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 9.0 Community Resources and Support\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some series revolve around the relationship between a band of influential figures and the community they protect. In defense of the community, they can {\b bolster}, expend, and juggle its various {\b resources}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These rules allow your GM to track the rise and fall of the fortunes of your community, and your impact on them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your GM intend to play a game centered around a community, you should have a relationship {\b ability} to that community.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is possible that you have relationships with other communities that are not the focus of play. Treat these relationships as {\b abilities} that you can call on, but your GM should not track these communities with these rules. Your GM should pick the level of community that provides the greatest dramatic potential from its competition for {\b resources}, friendly or otherwise, with its rivals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some campaigns do not center on a community, with the adventurers being footloose wanderers. In that case, even if you have community {\b abilities}, your GM will not track any community. Before you decide this though, consider where your PCs might turn for help, succor, or aid. Is there somewhere in the campaign defined as a place of refuge and safety for you. It may well be that there is a community, the bar where other footloose adventurers all meet, who will help each other out in a tight spot for example, that your GM can model.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 9.1 Community Design\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.1.1 Defining Resources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Communities have {\b resources} that your GM defines. Your PC can try to draw on their community\u8217's {\b resources} to use them as {\b bonus}. If your community is in difficulty, a strained {\b resource} might act as a {\b penalty}. Your GM should focus on no more than five or so broadly-labeled {\b resource} types, so that the PCs can care about (and have a chance of successfully managing) all of them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most communities have variants of the following {\b resources}, perhaps with more colorful names:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wealth \u8212- the capacity of the community to provide financial help, whether counted primarily in dollars, credits, or cattle\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Diplomacy \u8212- the relationships with other groups though which a community can obtain favors, while minimizing the cost of its reciprocal obligations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Morale \u8212- the community\u8217's resolve to achieve its goals, and willingness to follow the directives of its leaders\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following abilities might appear, depending on setting:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Military \u8212- its capacity to defend itself from outside threats, and to aggressively achieve its own aims through force of arms (for settings where communities of the size you\u8217're tracking field their own armed units)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Magic \u8212- the capability of a community to perform supernatural acts (for fantasy worlds)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Technology \u8212- its access to specialized, rare or secret devices or scientific knowledge not shared by its rivals (for post- apocalyptic or SF worlds)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similar communities in the genre, should have the same set of {\b resources}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.1.2 Assigning Ranks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM distributes the following {\b ranks} between the five {\b resources}: +M, +9, +6 +3 and 0. Note that the size of the group doesn\u8217't affect the {\b ranks}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.1.3 Community Questionnaires\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may create a questionnaire that asks the players to make choices about the priorities of their community. The responses to each question should be multiple-choice. Each choice you make adds points to a score for each {\b resource} type. Points are awarded according to what the answer reveals about the community\u8217's relative priorities. An answer may give points to more than one {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can choose your answers by consensus, majority vote, or take turns.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you\u8217're done, rank the {\b resources} in the order of the scores. Assign the high {\b ranks} to the highest {\b scores} and the lowest to the low.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A questionnaire also introduces your setting in a punchy, interactive format, and tailors the community to the players\u8217' desires, increasing their investment in it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 9.2 Drawing on Resources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use community {\b resources} as a {\b bonus} to your {\b abilities} after convincing the community to let you expend precious assets. This requires a preliminary {\b contest} using a social {\b ability}, most likely your community relationship. Your GM will use a {\b moderate resistance} as the baseline, with higher {\b resistance}s when your proposals seem selfish or likely to fail, and lower ones when everyone but the dullest dolt would readily see their collective benefits. Your GM may increase {\b resistance}s if your group draws constantly on community {\b resources} without replenishing them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lobbying effort and the actual resource use require framing, a clear description of what you are doing, and other details to bring them to fictional life. You cannot use {\b resource abilities} directly, but as an {\b bonus} to your own {\b abilities}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use of community {\b resources} should pass the threshold for being {\i memorable} and {\i entertaining}. Normally there should be a clear benefit to the community, or risk to the community. The PC\u8217's actions should be in support of the community, not themselves. Community involvement becomes part of the story. A certain amount of routine support for your character is assumed; a {\b bonus} implies that the community is expending abnormal effort on your behalf, that will cost the community itself.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.2.1 Resource Depletion\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike character abilities, each use of community {\b resources} temporarily {\b depletes} it. Regardless of {\b outcome} a {\b resource} drops a {\b rank} when used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM decides when a {\b resource} is restored to its original value. Your GM should decide what the credible interval is for the community to recover from the expenditure of effort. At that point, your GM restores the {\b bonus} for the {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You might chose to use a {\b resource} when it is already depleted, in which case you use its lower {\b rank}. Your GM may use this to represent attrition to your community from a continued struggle. A {\b resource} that is depleted enough, may become a {\b penalty}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Threats to community {\b resources} act as a spur to PC action. Your GM may rule that the {\b outcome} from a {\b contest} where you did not use the {\b resource} may still deplete the rank of a community {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.2.2 Required Resource Use\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As part of your GM\u8217's setting design, they may specify that certain actions in a setting always require the use of a community {\b resource}. Because the {\b resource} use is obligatory, it need not meet the usual criteria for entertainment value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.2.4 Resource as a Penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b resource\u8217's rank} may fall below 0. If you require use of a community\u8217's {\b resources} (see \u167?9.2.2) your actions will be subject to a {\b penalty} equal to the resource rank.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.2.4 Bolstering Resources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may offer you the opportunity to {\b bolster} a community {\b resources} ahead of need by seeking out and overcoming relevant {\b story obstacles}. If you succeed, the community resource improves a {\b rank}. Your GM will set the {\b resistance} for the {\b bolster}. The community\u8217's higher {\b ranked} resources should have higher {\b resistances} to {\b bolstering}. As a default, use the current {\b rank} as the resistance to {\b bolstering}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For clarity, a {\b resource} rated at +M can be bolstered to +M2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bolstering} lasts until the {\b resource} is used. When your GM depletes a {\b bolstered resource} following usage, they remove only the additional {\b rank} from {\b bolstering}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a {\b resource} is already suffering from a {\b penalty}, bolstering removes that {\b penalty} instead of improving the {\b rank}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 9.2.5 Background Events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the background all sorts of other events periodically alter the community\u8217's prosperity. These include the actions of other community members, who are {\b depleting and bolstering resources} all the time, as well as the unexpected intrusion of outside forces.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may decide that the community\u8217's {\b rank} in a {\b resource} is temporarily at a higher or lower {\b rank} due to these outside events. Your GM decides when the {\b resource} returns to normal. For a lower {\b rank}, this may require you to overcome a {\b story obstacle}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 10.0 Appendix\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 10.1 Glossary of Terms\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ability} Anything you can apply to solve a problem or overcome an obstacle\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Advance} A package of improvements to your {\b abilities} and {\b keywords} earned through {\b experience points} or {\b milestone advancement}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Advantage Point (AP)} A measure of advantage in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ally} A {\b supporting character} of roughly equal ability to your own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP} Abbreviation for Advantage Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP Gifting} When you help another character, whilst uninvolved in a {\b contest}, by giving them {\b advantage points} in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP Lending} When you help another character, whilst engaged in a {\b contest}, by lending them {\b advantage points}, in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Asymmetrical Exchange} In a {\b extended contest}, where you are pressed by an opponent, but want to do something other than contend directly for the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Asymmetrical Round} In a {\b scored contest}, where you are pressed by an opponent, but want to do something other than contend directly for the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Assist} In a {\b scored contest}, if you are unengaged you may use an {\b assist} to reduce the {\b resolution points} scored against another character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Augment} Using one {\b ability} to help another {\b ability}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Assured Contest} You have an appropriate {\b ability} and the GM feels {\b failure} is not interesting, or makes the PC looks un-heroic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Background Event} An off-stage {\b bonus} or {\b penalty} applied to a {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base resistance} The {\b TN} for a {\b moderate resistance class}, from which all other {\b resistance classes} are figured as a {\b bonus} or {\b penalty}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Benefit of Victory} Long term positive modifier, because you won a {\b contest}, against a challenging opponent (not -6 or less than your {\b ability}). Usually a {\b state of fortune}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bid} Also an {\b AP Bid} or {\b advantage point bid} is your wager in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bolster} A {\b story obstacle} to apply a bonus to a community {\b resource}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bonus} A positive modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Boost} Spending points after a {\b group simple contest outcome}, to improve the victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bump} An increment of the {\b result} of a roll, up or down. So a bump up moves a {\b fumble}, to a {\b failure}, to a {\b success} to a {\b critical}, a bump down moves a {\b critical}, to a {\b success}, to a {\b failure} to a {\b fumble}. One step is moved per {\b bump}. It is usually the impact of a {\b story point} or {\b mastery}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Burn} Using a {\b story point} as a bump. The {\b story point} is lost after burning.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Catch-Up} When you cross a {\b mastery} threshold you can increase lesser used {\b abilities} to ensure they keep pace.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Climax} A {\b long contest} {\b story obstacle} that provides the conclusion to a story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contact} A {\b supporting character} who shares an {\b occupation} or interest with your character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest} Where there is uncertainty as to whether a PC can overcome a {\b story obstacle} or discover a secret, then your GM can call for a contest to determine if the PC succeeds or fails. A contest may be {\b simple} (one roll) of {\b long} (a series of rolls).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b consequences} Long term negative modifier, because you lost a contest. Usually a {\b state of adversity}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest Framing} Setting the stakes of the {\b contest}, what is this conflict about. Often not the immediate aftermath of victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Credibility Test} Is it possible to perform the action without an {\b ability}, with an ordinary {\b ability}, or only with a {\b extraordinary ability}?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crisis Test} Used to determine if a {\b resource} that has a {\b penalty} creates a crisis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Defeat} Your {\b result} is worse than the {\b resistance\u8217's} result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Defensive Response} In a {\b scored contest} you can choose a defensive {\b tactic} which reduces the {\b resource points} you lose on a negative {\b result}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dependent} A {\b supporting character} who depends on your PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Depletion} Use of a community {\b resource} leads to its depletion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Directed Improvement} When your GM grants you a new {\b ability}, or an increase to an existing one, to recognize a story event.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Distinguishing Characteristic} The dominant personality {\b ability} that others recognize in a character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dying} A {\b state of adversity}, where the character\u8217's {\b defeat} will end their participation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Edge} In an {\b extended contest} adds to the {\b APs} lost or transferred when you win an {\b exchange}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Exchange} In an {\b extended contest} a round is divided into two {\b exchanges} where both aggressor and defender act. In a {\b group extended contest} a round consists of a sequence of {\b exchanges} where everyone acts in turn. The GM determines the order of action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extended Contest} A type of {\b long contest} in which you track the relative advantage one opponent has over another using {\b advantage points}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Experience Points (XP)} When you experience {\b defeat}, or a {\b flaw} you may gain an {\b experience point}, which accumulate between sessions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extraordinary ability} Certain genres allow player characters to have {\b abilities} that exceed human norms, these are {\b extraordinary abilities}. A genre pack normally outlines what is possible as part of its extraordinary powers framework.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Failure} Rolling over your {\b target number}. It can be a {\b fumble} or just a plain {\b failure}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Final Action} A last action by a {\b dying} character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flaw} An {\b ability} that penalizes you instead of helping you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fumble} The worst {\b failure} {\b result}, a notable failure either due to incompetence or bad luck.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Follower} A {\b supporting character} under your control. Either a {\b sidekick} or {\b retainer}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Framing the contest} You and your GM agree on the {\b prize} for the victor, and your tactic in trying to win it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Chained Contest} A {\b chained contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Extended Contest} An {\b extended contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Scored Contest} A {\b scored contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Simple Contest} A {\b simple contest} where one side has multiple participants.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Graduated Goals} When a contestant has a {\b primary} and {\b secondary} goal, and may have to choose between them if you have the same result as your opponent but a better roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Handicap} In an {\b extended contest} subtracts from the {\b APs} lost or transferred when you win an {\b exchange}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Story Point} Allows you to alter fate for a player character, either by a {\b bump} to their {\b result} or a {\b plot edit}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hurt} A state of adversity, a flesh wound or injured pride, heals at the end of a session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keyword} A single {\b ability} that encompasses a range of abilities within it, such as an {\b occupation} or culture. An {\b ability} within an {\b umbrella keyword} is a {\b break-out ability}, an {\b ability} within a {\b package keyword} is a {\b stand-alone ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Long Contest} A {\b contest} where we drill-down to the individual exchanges that resolve the conflict. We support {\b scored}, {\b extended}, and {\b chained contests}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Milestone Advancement} A method for improving a character where the GM declares when you receive an {\b advance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Modifiers} Adjustments to a {\b target number} due to circumstance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mastery} An {\b ability} {\b score} that rises above 20 is said to have a {\b mastery}. {\b Masteries} cancel each other out in {\b contests}. {\b Masteries} that are not cancelled provide a {\b bump}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mismatched Goals} When the opposing sides in a {\b contest} want different {\b prizes}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Occupation} An {\b ability} that indicates the profession, or primary area of expertise, of your character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Outcome} A {\b contest} has an {\b outcome}, described as a {\b victory} or {\b defeat} in obtaining the {\b prize} that was agreed in {\b contest framing} for any PCs involved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Parting Shot} An attempt to make your opponent\u8217's {\b defeat} worse in a {\b long contest} ({\b scored} or {\b extended}), by \u8216'finishing them off\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Patron} A {\b supporting character} with superior assets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Penalty} A negative modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Prize} What is at stake in the {\b contest}, decided during {\b framing}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rating} An ability has a {\b rating}, between 1 and 20, indicating how likely a character is to succeed at using it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance} The forces opposing the PC in a conflict, or concealing a secret that must be overcome by using an {\b ability} in a {\b contest}. One of: {\b Extreme}, {\b Huge}, {\b Very High}, {\b High}, {\b Raised}, {\b Moderate}, {\b Low}, {\b Very Low}, {\b Tiny}, {\b Rock-bottom}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance Class} The {\b bonus} or {\b penalty} to the {\b resistance} {\b TN}, depending on the GM\u8217's interpretation of how {\i dramatically} hard the {\b story obstacle} is.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resolution Point (RP)} In a {\b scored contest} an {\b RP} tracks the advantage one contestant has over the other.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resource} A community {\b ability} that your PC may draw on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Result} The {\b outcome} of a die roll against a {\b TN}. One of {\b critical}, {\b success}, {\b failure}, and {\b fumble}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Retainer} A {\b follower} of your PC who is not \u8216'fleshed out\u8217' and cannot act independently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rising Action} A {\b scored contest} where the {\b story obstacle} is a step towards the final {\b story obstacle} of this story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Risky Gambit} In a {\b long contest} you can take an action that puts you at more risk on defeat, but enhances victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Round} A {\b long contest} is broken into a series of rounds, each of which is an attempt to obtain the {\b prize}. In an {\b extended contest} a round is further broken into a number of {\b exchanges} in which all participants have the chance to act.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Score} A {\b score} consists of a {\b rating} and, if it is above 20, one or more {\b masteries}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Second Chance} An attempt by {\b defeated}, but unengaged, PCs to re-enter an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scored Contest} A {\b long contest} where we track the relative advantage one contestant has over another using {\b resolution points}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sidekick} A fleshed out {\b follower} of your PC who can act independently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Supporting Characters} Additional characters under the player\u8217's control that play a supporting role to their PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Simple Contest} A one roll resolution method, the default {\b contest} type, used when learning the {\b outcome} matters more than the breakdown of how you achieved it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Stand Alone Ability} An {\b ability} raised separately to a {\b keyword}. It may have been added to the character as part of a {\b package keyword}, or on its own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Story Obstacle} Something that prevents you from getting what you want, the {\b prize}. A {\b story obstacle} is the trigger for a {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Stretch} A {\b penalty} applied to an {\b ability} because it is stretches credibility that it is a reasonable {\b tactic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Success} Rolling under your {\b target number}. It can be a {\b critical} or just a plain {\b success}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tactic} How you intend to use one of your {\b abilities} to overcome a {\b story obstacle}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Target Number (TN)} The number, either an {\b ability} {\b rating}, or a {\b resistance}, to roll under or equal to in order to {\b succeed}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b TN} Abbreviation for {\b Target Number}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Unrelated Action} An action when you are disengaged in a {\b long contest} that does not relate to your attempt to win the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Victory} Your {\b result} is a better roll than the {\b resistance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 10.2 Version Changes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Version 3.0\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These are the major changes in this version of the rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Split hero points into story points (bumps) and experience points (character improvement). Flaws generate experience points as do failures.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Moved the Degree of Victory to an Appendix. We now recommend that the GM just uses victory and defeat and adjudicates a suitable bonus or penalty if needed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added ranks to codify the +3, +6, +9, \u8230? progression used throughout.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For Degree of Victory, clarified that contest results are only reciprocal between PCs. When the contest is against a resistance set by the GM, the results indicate whether the PC gains the prize, and the GM narrates the result for the resistance based on this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Rephrased the Degree of Victory outcomes to emphasize: Yes, No, And\u8230?, But\u8230?, This change is designed to dissuade GMs from misunderstanding that the prize is obtained on a marginal victory, one of the most common result types, and instead encourage GMs to allow PCs to fail forward on such a result by introducing downstream complications.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Provided clarity that consequences of defeat and benefit of victory are optional and the GM should focus on using the prize to narrate the outcome of a contest, only applying mechanical benefits if they make sense.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For use with Degrees of Victory, added States of Fortune to mirror States of Adversity. Overall mirrored benefits and consequences more closely\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Specific Ability Bonuses are dropped. They were hard for the GM to adjudicate and the same intent is better served by using a stretch on a broad ability when contesting against a PC with a more specific ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A winning group in a Group Simple Contest does not suffer a Consequence of Defeat as a result of a low RP difference victory any more, the GM should narrate consequences from the level of victory, if appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Dropped the negative consequences for the winner in an Extended Contest during the Rising Action. If the winner is a PC the different results suggest additional consequences. So this rule is an over-complication.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Made it clear that only a PC should use a parting shot, not the resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Long contests include both extended contest and scored contests. Between version 1 and version 2 extended contests switched to scored contests, this approach restores both variants, but requires changing the generic name to a long contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Dropped edges and handicaps from extended contests - we use a resistance not stats, so makes no sense to have edges and handicaps\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added alternate mechanisms for determining if resistance advances and when\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added story-based resistance mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added story-based improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added Mythic Russia\u8217's Plot Edits\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Added Mythic Russia\u8217's Pyrrhic Victories for Extended Contests but as Climatic Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Changed degree of success and failure, to degree of victory and defeat, as success and failure are for individual rolls, victory and defeat once compared.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Simplified how multiple opponents are handled\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Clarified contest outcomes for long contests, and how to determine the overall winner in a long contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Do not allow transfers in an extended contest where the abilities differ by 6 or more. Consistent with benefits of victory and prevents \u8216'loading up on mooks\u8217' as a strategy.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 10.3 Outcomes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Prior versions of the {\i QuestWorlds} rules determined a {\b degree of victory} by comparing PC and {\b resistance} {\b results}. We now recommend just having a {\b victory} or {\b defeat} an narrating from the individual {\b results} as faster and simpler in play. But for those who prefer the older approach, or want to maintain compatibility with it, we present those rules in this appendix.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.3.1 Degree of Victory or Defeat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Often all you need to know to interpret the {\b outcome} of a resolution is whether you gained {\b victory} or suffered a {\b defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes, you\u8217'll want to know how great a {\b victory} you won, or how bad a {\b defeat} you endured. This may be important in providing {\b consequences or benefits} that drive further story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All of the resolution methods have an option to yield the {\b Degree of Victor or Defeat} for the PC. The possible {\b Degree of Victory or Defeat}, from least to greatest, are: {\b marginal}, {\b minor}, {\b major}, {\b complete}. {\b Ties} are also possible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you struggle against NPCs or abstract forces, the interpretation of the {\b outcome} reveals whether you overcome the {\b story obstacle}, and any {\b consequences or benefits}; your GM narrates the fate of the NPCs or other forces depending on what makes sense. However, when you and another PC engage in a {\b contest} then a {\b victory} for one contestant means a corresponding {\b defeat} for the loser.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 So whilst in a PC vs.\u160?PC duel the PC would only be killed on a {\b complete defeat}, an NPC, described as a {\b resistance}, might be killed on any {\b victory}, depending on how the {\b contest} was framed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tie}: Tie means no {\b outcome}. Effort was expended, but the net {\b outcome} is that nothing consequential occurs, or else both sides lose or gain equally. If this is confusing, and you are not contending with another PC, your GM can rule that you gain a {\b marginal victory}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Victory}: Yes, but\u8230? You get what you want, the {\b prize}, but there are complications, the effect is more limited than you desired, or you have to make a hard choice between benefits or accept a loss to get one\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Victory}: Yes\u8230? You get exactly what they want i.e.\u160?whatever was the {\b prize} in the {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major & Complete Victory}: Yes, and\u8230? You get the {\b prize}, and something else. You gain something, stealing a possession, gaining a new {\b follower}, or become renowned in song. If you want to distinguish a {\b complete} the effect is often permanent and no new {\b contests} should be framed for this {\b story obstacle}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Defeat}: No, but\u8230? You don\u8217't get what you want, you lose the {\b prize}, but it\u8217's not a total loss. You are able to salvage something from the {\b defeat}, a little more if you sacrifice something other than the {\b prize} to your opponent, that the opponent agrees to take instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Defeat}: No\u8230? You don\u8217't get what you want, you lose the {\b prize}. Any consequences or complications such as injury or loss of influence are short term and easily shrugged off. Just take the loss and rest up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major & Complete Defeat}: No and\u8230? You don\u8217't get what you want, you lose the {\b prize}, and there are long-term consequences. The situation might grow worse or more complicated or you might suffer adverse consequences that will require other conflicts to resolve: an injury that needs a healer, an insult that requires a formal apology, a loss of influence with the community that requires a triumph to win their trust again etc. You might be dead, or as good as. The {\b prize} is likely lost to you permanently. Or perhaps you lose something, an item is taken from you, a {\b follower} deserts you, your reputation lies in ruins as poets mock your defeat. If you want to distinguish, a {\b complete} should be bigger loss than a {\b major}, but you can often ignore this distinction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will use the {\b degree of success} to determine any {\b benefits and consequences}, but be sure to describe the {\b success} in narrative terms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are using a {\b stretch}, see \u167?2.4.1, then {\b major or complete victories} you obtain are instead treated as {\b minor victories}.\par}
