{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.3.3.3 Boosting Outcomes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because they average together the {\b outcomes} of multiple participants, {\b group simple contests} tend to flatten {\b outcomes}, making {\b victories} more likely to be {\b marginal} or {\b minor} than {\b major} or {\b complete}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To overcome this flattening effect, if the outcome of a {\b group simple contest} is a {\b tie} or {\b victory}, you may spend one or more {\b story points} to purchase a {\b boost}; a {\b boost} assures a clearer victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The cost varies by the number of PCs participating:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 {\b story point} for 1-3 PCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 2 {\b story points} for 4-6 PCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 3 {\b story points} for 7-9 PCs.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab and so on\u8230?\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may spend twice as many {\b story points} as required to gain a {\b double boost}. The points may be spent by any combination of players. They remain spent no matter how the {\b contest} resolves. You may continue to spend {\b story points} to {\b bump} your individual {\b result}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b boost} increases the collective {\b victory} level by one step. A {\b double boost} increases it by two steps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.3.4 Scored Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a {\b scored contest} you compare the difference between the winner\u8217's {\b resolution points} and the loser\u8217's {\b resolution points} to determine the {\b outcome}. You use one of two tables {\b rising action} (see \u167?9.2.) or {\b climax} depending on the dramatic arc of your story.\par}
