{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.3.5 Group Scored Contest Outcomes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a {\b group scored contest} the side that has the last undefeated contestant gains the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the PCs won, determine the group\u8217's overall {\b outcome} by using the second-best {\b outcome} obtained by the PCs, or if there is only one opponent, the {\b outcome}. If the PCs lost, determine the group\u8217's overall {\b outcome} by using the second-worst outcome obtained by the PCs, or if there is only one PC, the {\b outcome}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i For example, your PC Lieutenant Jackson of the Royal Navy has led a shore-action against a French outpost. Lieutenant Jackson and two other PCs have {\b victory} {\b outcomes} at the end of the contest, so the Royal Navy wins the day. To determine how well the Royal Navy has done your GM looks at the three {\b victorious} {\b outcomes} for the Royal Navy, a {\b major victory}, a {\b minor victory} and a {\b marginal victory}. The second best outcome is a {\b minor victory} so your GM declares that the Royal Navy have a {\b minor victory} and have overrun the French outpost, but gained little else.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Later you lead your men in a spirited defense against a French boarding action of your ship. However, the French win the day, with Lieutenant Jackson and the other PCs suffering {\b defeat} {\b outcomes} at the end of the {\b contest}. Looking at your PCs {\b outcomes} there is a {\b major defeat}, two {\b minor defeats} and a {\b marginal defeat}. The French win the day with a {\b minor defeat} for your Royal Navy crew.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To determine individual {\b consequences} or {\b benefits}, in {\b rising action}, even if you engage multiple opponents in a {\b rising action scored contest}, only use the last opponent you engaged to determine your individual {\b outcome}. In a climatic contest total the {\b resolution points} scored against you by all your opponents. If you engage more than one opponent, be sure to add the {\b resolution points} scored against you by all of them. If you lost, add 1 to your total. Your GM cross-references the total against the {\b climactic state of adversity} table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.3.6 Extended Contest Outcomes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At the end of the contest the {\b APs} of the loser determine the {\b benefits} for the winner or {\b consequences} for the loser. As with all {\b contests}, if the contest involved a {\b resistance}, and not another PC, we care about your {\b outcome}, win or lose, and the GM should feel free to narrate the {\b outcome} for the {\b resistance} depending on their interpretation of your {\b outcome}, which may not be symmetrical. For example, if the {\b benefit of victory} for your PC is {\b pumped} the GM should feel free to interpret what this means for the {\b resistance}: in a melee they might be dead, in a social contest they might be exiled, or they might surrender in the melee or cede ground in a social contest. Your GM should focus on the {\b prize} that was agreed when deciding how to narrate the resolution of the contest.\par}
