{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 10.6 Community Rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The community rules in earlier versions were complex and have been simplified in the current rules. They are presented here mainly to help in understanding older material, or for those who prefer it\u8217's more complex tracking approach.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.1 Defining Resources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Communities can have a type of {\b ability} called a {\b resource} that your GM defines. Your PC can try to draw on their community\u8217's {\b resources} to use them as {\b abilities}. Your GM should focus on no more than five or so broadly-labeled {\b resource} types, so that the PCs can care about (and have a chance of successfully managing) all of them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.2 Specify an interval\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM chooses a suitable interval to mark changes in {\b resources}. For genres bound by the agricultural season, this is usually a season, for a military genre it might be a campaign, for a ship a voyage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.3 Assigning Ability Scores\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM distributes the following {\b scores} between the five abilities: 12W, 9W, 18, 18, and 12. Note that the size of the group doesn\u8217't affect the {\b scores}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.4 Resource Notation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will keep track of {\b modifiers} to community {\b resources} with a copy of the following record sheet. They will use a pencil, because the numbers will fluctuate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM lists the names and {\b scores} of your chosen {\b resources} in the first row. Under the total column for each, your GM will list the total current modifier. Under the PC column, your GM lists {\b bonuses} resulting from PC activities (as opposed to un-cemented {\b background events}.) When PCs {\b cement a background benefit}, your GM adds its bonus to the PC column.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When PC activity reduces a {\b penalty} but does not eliminate it, your GM will alter the entry under the Total column to reflect the reduction, but leave the PC column blank.\par}
