{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Except where your group is exceptionally keen on tracking {\b resources}, your GM should skip the {\b background events} process when the PCs are long absent from home. Your GM should rejigger them to serve their plot purposes when they return. The GM may also want to shuffle this process offstage when the PCs are occupied by epic events. This prevents them from having to flee from a climactic plot development to go home and tend to the beet crop.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.10 Crisis Tests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When {\b resources} endure {\b penalties}, you conduct a {\b crisis test} at the beginning of each game session to see if trouble strikes the community. A high but {\b penalized score} can still lead to crisis, because people have adjusted to the equilibrium it offers and feel squeezed when it shifts on them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b crisis test} is a {\b simple contest} (one for each {\b penalized ability}) of the {\b resource score} against a {\b resistance} equal to the average of all {\b resource scores}. Like {\b background event} checks, these can\u8217't be {\b augmented} or {\b bumped} up by player action. On any {\b defeat}, the community starts to visibly suffer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM invents the specific reasons for each fluctuation and narrates them to you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crisis tests} should spur you to action, challenging you to find ways to {\b bolster} the affected {\b resources} (see above). When {\b bolstered}, the {\b crisis} is reversed. If you neglect your duties or fail, the {\b crisis} worsens.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will call for {\b crisis tests} only as needed, as a tool to generate story. If your group already has enough story on its hands, your GM will suspend them until you next need a new plot hook.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.11 Cementing Benefits of Background Events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bonuses} from {\b background events} are temporary, unless you take steps to {\b cement your benefits}. Doing so requires you to overcome a major {\b story obstacle}, perhaps taking focus for an evening\u8217's worth of play. If you succeed, the {\b background event bonus} may, as per the next section, later solidify into a permanent increase in the {\b resource\u8217's score}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you {\b cement a background bonus}, your GM changes their notation of that {\b bonus}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.12 Changes to Resource Scores\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At the end of your GM\u8217's chosen interval, they review the Resource Notation Table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any {\b resource} with a {\b bonus} of 3 or more in its PC column increases by 1 for each 3 points of {\b bonus}, for a maximum increase of 3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any {\b resource} with a {\b penalty} in its Total column decreases by 1 for each 3 points of {\b penalty}, for a maximum loss of 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any remaining {\b modifiers} are now reduced to 0.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GM now start a new Resource Notation Table, with {\b resource scores} altered to reflect any changes from the above process.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Having made permanent changes to the community\u8217's {\b resource scores}, your GM then restarts the cycle by again testing for a new set of {\b background events}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 10.6.13 Changes from Plot Events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may decide that certain remarkable triumphs or horrifying catastrophes may directly alter a {\b resource score}, independent of the resource tracking system given here. The possibility of a dramatic swing in community fortunes should be made clear by your GM during {\b contest framing}, so that you know the {\b prize} and can pull out all the stops to secure {\b victory} or stave off {\b defeat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 10.7 Additional Terms\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following terms are for rules in the appendix that are no longer used in the main rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest of Wherewithal} A {\b contest} that allows a {\b dying} character to complete one {\b final action}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Complete Defeat} No, and\u8230?. You have lost, and the impact is long-lasting, maybe even fatal or terminal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Complete Victory} Yes, and\u8230? You have won, and the impact is long-lasting, possibly a permanent change in your favor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Degree of Victory or Defeat} How well did you triumph, or how badly did you fail: {\b marginal}, {\b minor}, {\b major}, {\b complete}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major Defeat} No, and. You have lost, and the impact is long-lasting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major Victory}, Yes, and. You have won, and the impact is long-lasting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Defeat} No, but\u8230? You don\u8217't get what you want, but the damage may be mitigated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Victory} Yes, but\u8230? You get what you want, but you may have to make a hard choice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Defeat} No\u8230? you don\u8217't get the agreed {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Victory} Yes\u8230? you get the agreed {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Outcome Point} A point scored in favor one side in a {\b group simple contest}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b State of Adversity} How \u8216'banged up\u8217' a PC is, physically or metaphorically, following a {\b defeat}: {\b Hurt}, {\b Injured}, {\b Impaired}, {\b Dying} and {\b Dead}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b State of Fortune} A \u8216'boost\u8217' to the PC which may be physical or metaphorical.\par}
